<P>Instruct. II. <HI>Hence they all whose Hap|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">iness is in Earthly Enjoyments are Mi|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">rable men.</HI> They whose Names are written on the Earth, and whose Por|tion is in things here below are Mi|serable men indeed; Psal. 17.14. <HI>The men of the world, whose Portion is in this Life.</HI> They whose Portion is in this life, suppose them to have never so great a Portion, if that be all, they are very miserable. As indeed for the most part it is so, that they who have much of this world given to them, that is their Portion; that is all the Good they must ever enjoy&punc; therefore miserable are they. Christ sayes of
